To run sentiment_parse:

1) Install nltk:
   sudo pip install -U nltk

2) Install nltk data, beware it takes a while:
   sudo python -m nltk.downloader -d /usr/local/share/nltk_data all

3) Specify the path of the dictionary files, for example:
   export OPENCOG_PATH="$OPENCOG_PATH:$OPENCOG_REPO/opencog/"

4) run nlp-parse, follow the InheritanceLink to check the sentiment of the sentence:
guile> (cog-incoming-set (car (nlp-parse "This is not a disgusting test.")))
((InheritanceLink
   (SentenceNode "sentence@d6584821-3683-47a5-b77f-8971e20db8cb")
   (ConceptNode "Positive")
)
 (ParseLink (stv 1 1)
   (ParseNode "sentence@d6584821-3683-47a5-b77f-8971e20db8cb_parse_0" (stv 1 0.61070001))
   (SentenceNode "sentence@d6584821-3683-47a5-b77f-8971e20db8cb")
)
 (SentenceSequenceLink (stv 1 1)
   (SentenceNode "sentence@d6584821-3683-47a5-b77f-8971e20db8cb")
   (NumberNode "612.000000")
)
 (ListLink
   (Node "This is not a disgusting test.")
   (SentenceNode "sentence@d6584821-3683-47a5-b77f-8971e20db8cb")
)
)


To load sentiment word list:

1) using the same OPENCOG_PATH as running the sentiment parse to specify the path of the simplified ictionary file "sentiWordNet", i.e

2) load the sentiment word list from sentiWordNet file:

(load "../opencog/nlp/chatbot/loadSentiList.scm")

3) check if it's correctly loaded:

guile> (cog-incoming-set (cog-node 'ConceptNode "comparative"))
((InheritanceLink (stv 0.75 0.89999998)
   (ConceptNode "comparative")
   (ConceptNode "Negative")
)
 (InheritanceLink (stv 0.625 0.89999998)
   (ConceptNode "comparative")
   (ConceptNode "Positive")
)
)
